# Basic SCSS

## Variables

Use `$name: value;` for colours, spacing, breakpoints. Use once, change everywhere.

```scss
$primary: #3b82f6;
$spacing-md: 1rem;
$breakpoint-tablet: 768px;

.button { background: $primary; padding: $spacing-md; }
```

## Nesting

Nest selectors for clearer structure. Keep nesting shallow (max 2–3 levels) to avoid deep specificity.

```scss
.card {
  padding: 1rem;
  .card-title { font-weight: 600; }
  .card-body { margin-top: 0.5rem; }
}
```

Use `&` for pseudo-classes or parent reference:

```scss
.btn {
  &:hover { opacity: 0.9; }
  &.active { font-weight: bold; }
}
```

## Partials and @use

Split styles into partials (names starting with `_`). Import with `@use` (prefer over `@import`).

```scss
// _variables.scss
$primary: #3b82f6;

// main.scss
@use 'variables' as v;
.button { background: v.$primary; }
```

## Mixins (optional)

Use for repeated patterns (e.g. breakpoints, clearfix). Don’t overuse.

```scss
@mixin respond-to($width) {
  @media (min-width: $width) { @content; }
}
.sidebar { @include respond-to(768px) { width: 50%; } }
```

## Rules

- Prefer variables over magic numbers and repeated colours.
- Avoid nesting more than 3 levels.
- Use `@use` instead of `@import` for modules.
- Keep mixins for real repetition; otherwise plain CSS or variables are enough.
